net.enilink.komma.core

Interface IGraph

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Collection<IStatement>, Iterable<IStatement>, Serializable, Set<IStatement>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    LinkedHashGraph, LinkedHashGraph.EmptyGraph, LinkedHashGraph.FilteredGraph

    public interface IGraph
extends Set<IStatement>, Serializable
    An RDF graph, represented as a set of IStatements with predictable iteration order.

    • Method Detail

      • contains

        boolean contains(IReference subj,
                 IReference pred,
                 Object obj,
                 IReference... contexts)
        Determines if statements with the specified subject, predicate, object and (optionally) context exist in this graph. The subject, predicate and object parameters can be null to indicate wildcards. The contexts parameter is a wildcard and accepts zero or more values. If no contexts are specified, statements will match disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will match. Note: to match statements without an associated context, specify the value null and explicitly cast it to type Resource.

        Examples: graph.contains(s1, null, null) is true if any statements in this graph have subject s1,
        graph.contains(null, null, null, c1) is true if any statements in this graph have context c1,
        graph.contains(null, null, null, (Resource)null) is true if any statements in this graph have no associated context,
        graph.contains(null, null, null, c1, c2, c3) is true if any statements in this graph have context c1, c2 or c3.

        Parameters:
        subj - The subject of the statements to match, null to match statements with any subject.
        pred - The predicate of the statements to match, null to match statements with any predicate.
        obj - The object of the statements to match, null to match statements with any object.
        contexts - The contexts of the statements to match. If no contexts are specified, statements will match disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will match.
        Returns:
        true if statements match the specified pattern.

      • add

        boolean add(IReference subj,
            IReference pred,
            Object obj,
            IReference... contexts)
        Adds one or more statements to the graph. This method creates a statement for each specified context and adds those to the graph. If no contexts are specified, a single statement with no associated context is added. If this graph is a filtered graph then null (if context empty) values are permitted and will used the corresponding filtered values.
        Parameters:
        subj - The statement's subject.
        pred - The statement's predicate.
        obj - The statement's object.
        contexts - The contexts to add statements to.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If this graph cannot store the given statement, because it is filtered out of this view.
        UnsupportedOperationException - If this graph cannot accept any statements, because it is filter to the empty set.

        true if one or more statements have been removed.

      • remove

        boolean remove(IReference subj,
               IReference pred,
               Object obj,
               IReference... contexts)
        Removes statements with the specified subject, predicate, object and (optionally) context exist in this graph. The subject, predicate and object parameters can be null to indicate wildcards. The contexts parameter is a wildcard and accepts zero or more values. If no contexts are specified, statements will be removed disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will be removed. Note: to remove statements without an associated context, specify the value null and explicitly cast it to type Resource.

        Examples: graph.remove(s1, null, null) removes any statements in this graph have subject s1,
        graph.remove(null, null, null, c1) removes any statements in this graph have context c1,
        graph.remove(null, null, null, (Resource)null) removes any statements in this graph have no associated context,
        graph.remove(null, null, null, c1, c2, c3) removes any statements in this graph have context c1, c2 or c3.

        Parameters:
        subj - The subject of the statements to remove, null to remove statements with any subject.
        pred - The predicate of the statements to remove, null to remove statements with any predicate.
        obj - The object of the statements to remove, null to remove statements with any object.
        contexts - The contexts of the statements to remove. If no contexts are specified, statements will be removed disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will be removed.
        Returns:
        true if one or more statements have been removed.

      • filter

        IGraph filter(IReference subj,
              IReference pred,
              Object obj,
              IReference... contexts)
        Returns a view of the statements with the specified subject, predicate, object and (optionally) context. The subject, predicate and object parameters can be null to indicate wildcards. The contexts parameter is a wildcard and accepts zero or more values. If no contexts are specified, statements will match disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will match. Note: to match statements without an associated context, specify the value null and explicitly cast it to type Resource.

        The returned graph is backed by this graph, so changes to this graph are reflected in the returned graph, and vice-versa. If this graph is modified while an iteration over the returned graph is in progress (except through the iterator's own remove operation), the results of the iteration are undefined. The graph supports element removal, which removes the corresponding statement from this graph, via the Iterator.remove, Set.remove, removeAll, retainAll, and clear operations. The statements passed to the add and addAll operations must match the parameter pattern.

        Examples: graph.filter(s1, null, null) matches all statements that have subject s1,
        graph.filter(null, null, null, c1) matches all statements that have context c1,
        graph.filter(null, null, null, (Resource)null) matches all statements that have no associated context,
        graph.filter(null, null, null, c1, c2, c3) matches all statements that have context c1, c2 or c3.

        Parameters:
        subj - The subject of the statements to match, null to match statements with any subject.
        pred - The predicate of the statements to match, null to match statements with any predicate.
        obj - The object of the statements to match, null to match statements with any object.
        contexts - The contexts of the statements to match. If no contexts are specified, statements will match disregarding their context. If one or more contexts are specified, statements with a context matching one of these will match.
        Returns:
        The statements that match the specified pattern.

      • subjects

        Set<IReference> subjects()
        Returns a Set view of the subjects contained in this graph. The set is backed by the graph, so changes to the graph are reflected in the set, and vice-versa. If the graph is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress (except through the iterator's own remove operation), the results of the iteration are undefined. The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding statement from the graph, via the Iterator.remove, Set.remove, removeAll, retainAll, and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations if the parameters pred or obj are null.
        Returns:
        a set view of the subjects contained in this graph

      • objectValue

        Object objectValue()
        Gets the object of the statement(s). If contains one or more statements, all these statements should have the same object. A KommaException is thrown if this is not the case.
        Returns:
        The object of the matched statement(s), or null if no matching statements were found.
        Throws:
        KommaException - If the statements matched by the specified parameters have more than one unique object.
